ic forenames:  Scandinavian Nels.","Norwegian: old variant of <b>Barsnes</b> (and, in North America, probably also an altered form of this), a habitational name from a farmstead so named in the county of Sogn og Fjordane, possibly from a compound of the Old Norse personal name <i>Baldrekr</i> + <i>nes</i> ‘point, headland’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Caen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Manx: from Gaelic <i>Mac Catháin</i> ‘son of Cathan’, see   Kane  . The personal name literally meant ‘warrior’, a derivative of Manx <i>cah</i> ‘battle’ (Irish <i>cath</i>).","English: variant of   Cane  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from the city of Caen in Calvados, France."],"variants":[{"name":"Kayne","meanings":["English: elaborated spelling of   Cain  ."]},{"name":"Cane","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Caen in Calvados (France). See also   Cain   and   Cam  .","English: from a Middle English survival of the Old English personal name <i>Cana</i>, which is probably of ancient Germanic origin.","English: nickname for a tall thin man, from Middle English, Old French <i>cane</i> ‘cane, reed’ (from Latin <i>canna</i>). It may also be a metonymic occupational name for someone who gathered reeds, which were widely used in the Middle Ages as a floor covering, as roofing material, and for weaving small baskets."]},{"name":"Kane","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Padraic, Brennan, Declan, Donovan, Fergus, James Patrick, Keelin, Kieran, Siobhan.","Irish and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Catháin</b> or <b>Mac Catháin</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Cathán</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘warrior’ (see   O'Kane  ). Compare   Keane  .","English: variant of   Cane  ."]},{"name":"Caine","meanings":["Manx: from Gaelic <i>Mac Catháin</i> ‘son of Cathan’, see   Kane  . The personal name literally meant ‘warrior’, a derivative of Manx <i>cah</i> ‘battle’ (Irish <i>cath</i>).","English: variant of   Cane  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from the city of Caen in Calvados, France."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dynan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Dinan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dinan","meanings":["Irish (now mainly counties Clare and Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Daghnáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Daghnán</i>’, possibly a diminutive of <i>dagh</i> ‘good’.","Irish: variant of   Dineen  .","French: habitational name from Dinan, in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"Melette","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: altered form of   Mollet  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mollet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Jean Claude.","French and Swiss French: topographic name for someone who lived in a muddy or boggy place, from a diminutive of <i>mol</i> ‘marsh, bog’ (compare   Molle  ). This surname is also found in Germany.","English: variant of   Mollett  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":18,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","descripti